<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="43.[264,1322,1450,1756]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Remarks. This Neotropical genus consists of only 7 species, one of which is reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[264,330,1490,1516]" name="Cuba" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Cuba</collectingCountry>
. Here we report the genus and a new species from 
<collectingCountry box="[944,1119,1490,1516]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">the Dominican</collectingCountry>
Republic for the first time. The genus is distinguished by its size (
<quantity box="[840,970,1530,1556]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" unit="mm" value="17.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="15.0">15–20 mm</quantity>
) laterally flat proboscis, short pile, greatly reduced bristles, strongly constricted abdomen, and very long antenna. The scape is usually 10 times as long as the pedicel, and the flagellum is 1.2–2 times the length of the scape and pedicel combined (
<bibRefCitation author="Hull, F. M." box="[684,815,1650,1676]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 907" refId="ref42030" refString="Hull, F. M. (1962) Robber flies of the world. The genera of the family Asilidae. Smithsonian Institution Bulletin, 224, 1 - 907, 2536 figs." type="book chapter" year="1962">Hull, 1962</bibRefCitation>
). Species inhabit mature forest below 1500 meters, perching on shaded dead and live tree trunks (
<bibRefCitation author="Fisher, E. M. &amp; Hespenheide, H." box="[942,1317,1690,1716]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" pagination="610 - 613" refId="ref41860" refString="Fisher, E. M. &amp; Hespenheide, H. (1992) Taxonomy and biology of Central American robber flies with an illustrated key to the genera (Diptera: Asilidae). In Quintero Arias, D. and Aiello, A. (editors). Insects of Panama and Meso-America. Oxford University Press, Oxford, New York, Tokyo. 610 - 613 pp." type="book chapter" year="1992">Fisher and Hespenheide, 1992</bibRefCitation>
; Fisher, in press).
</paragraph>
